{{Infobox settlement |official_name = Seleka |image_skyline = |pushpin_map = Botswana |mapsize = 200px |map_caption = Location of Seleka in Botswana |subdivision_type = Country |subdivision_name = [[Botswana]] |subdivision_type1 = [[Districts of Botswana|District]] |subdivision_name1 = [[Central District (Botswana)|Central District]] |leader_title = Mayor |leader_name = |population_as_of = 2012 |population_total = |population_footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.world-gazetteer.com/wg.php?x=&men=gcis&lng=en&des=wg&geo=-42&srt=pnan&col=abcdefghinoq&msz=1500&pt=c&va=&srt=1pnan|title=2011 Census|archiveurl=https://archive.is/GsSXM|archivedate=11 Jan 2013}}</ref> |elevation_m = 1009 |area_total = |timezone = GMT +2 |coordinates = {{coord|23|06|S|26|48|E|region:BW|display=inline}} }}
'''Seleka''' is a village in near [[Mahalapye]] in the [[Central District, Botswana|Central District]] of [[Botswana]]. It derives its name from the name of one of the four subgroups of the [[Rolong]] people.<ref>Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Africa and the Middle East - Page 615 2009 "Seleka. The Seleka are one of the four main subgroups of the Rolong. The Rolong are a Tswana people of Southern Africa."</ref> Seleka had 1157 inhabitants in 2011<ref>Botswana Central Statistics Office [//www.cso.gov.bw/media/2011%20Census%20_Alphabetical%20Index%20_Population%20of%20Localities.pdf]</ref>
The area was previously grouped under Tumasera - with four villages: Tubjwa, Malete, Seleka and Rasesa, but Seleka was given autonomy in 2006<ref>{{en icon}} « Botswana: Hope for Peace At Tumasera-Seleka », Mmegi, 31 juillet 2006 [http://allafrica.com/stories/200607311492.html]</ref> and given separate census in 2011.<ref>« Census opens old wounds in Tumasera and Seleka », Mmegi Online, 19 Aug 2011 [http://www.mmegi.bw/index.php?sid=1&aid=1111&dir=2011/August/Friday19]</ref><ref>''Groundwater Development in [[Ramokgonami]] and Seleka Villages, Central District: Rural Village Water Supply Programme, Final Report'', Water Resources Consultants (Pty) Ltd, Gaborone, 2000</ref> {{Portal|Botswana}}
