{{italic title}}
'''''The Great Cat and Dog Massacre''''' is a non-fiction book written by [[Hilda Kean]]. It tells the story of  the September 1939 time period at the start of [[World War II]], when hundreds of thousands of [[United Kingdom|British]] family pets were preemptively [[euthanized]] in anticipation of air raids and resource shortages.<ref>[https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-pets-war-on-hilda-keans-the-great-cat-and-dog-massacre/ "The Pets’ War: On Hilda Kean’s “The Great Cat and Dog Massacre”"]. ''LA Review of Books'', April 30, 2017 By Colin Dickey</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/home/books/article-4474628/England-expects-kill-dog.html "England expects you to kill the dog (and eat your pet rabbit): Bizarre new read reveals the grisly fate of Britain's domestic animals in World War II"]. ''Daily Mail'',  John Preston, 4 May 2017</ref>

Kean also uses the episode to discuss people's feelings about their pets and the psychology of a population at war.<ref>[http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/05/08/shattered-the-great-cat-and-dog-massacre-number-11-and-a-little-more-human "Briefly Noted"]. ''The New Yorker'', May 8, 2017.</ref>

The book was published in 2017 by University of Chicago Press.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/21/books/review/great-cat-and-dog-massacre-hilda-kean.html "Keep Calm and Kiss the Cat Goodbye"]. ''New York Times'', Elena Passarello, April 21, 2017</ref> Its title is a reference to [[Robert Darnton]]'s 1984 work ''[[The Great Cat Massacre]]''.

